+++ b/RESULTS.md
@@ -0,0 +1,77 @@
+# Lottery Scheduling Results
+
+## 1. Setup
+
+- OS: MIT xv6-public (x86)
+- Scheduler: Modified to Lottery Scheduling
+- PRNG: Simple in-kernel LCG
+- System calls added:
+  - settickets(int n)
+  - getrtime()
+
+## 2. Experiment Design
+
+Two CPU-bound child processes were created.
+
+Ticket configuration:
+- Child A: 10 tickets
+- Child B: 30 tickets
+
+Each child:
+- Calls settickets(n)
+- Runs a tight CPU-bound loop
+- Competes for CPU for a fixed duration using uptime()
+- Reports the increase in rtime (CPU time consumed)
+
+Expected theoretical CPU share ratio:
+
+30 / 10 = 3.0
+
+## 3. Results
+
+### Duration = 500 ticks
+
+Run 1:
+- A = 138
+- B = 384
+- Ratio = 2.78 (approx)
+
+Run 2:
+- A = 130
+- B = 377
+- Ratio = 2.90 (approx)
+
+Run 3:
+- A = 117
+- B = 395
+- Ratio = 3.38 (approx)
+
+### Duration = 2000 ticks
+
+Run 1:
+- A = 549
+- B = 1517
+- Ratio = 2.76 (approx)
+
+Run 2:
+- A = 530
+- B = 1474
+- Ratio = 2.78 (approx)
+
+Run 3:
+- A = 518
+- B = 1494
+- Ratio = 2.88 (approx)
+
+## 4. Observations
+
+- Lottery scheduling distributes CPU proportionally to ticket count.
+- Short runs show noticeable variance due to randomness.
+- Longer runs converge toward the theoretical ratio.
+- No starvation was observed.
+- All usertests passed successfully.
+
+## 5. Conclusion
+
+The lottery scheduler correctly enforces proportional CPU allocation.
+The implementation maintains scheduler invariants and operates safely under ptable.lock.
